<font color=#6F6F6F>(7/24/02 9:38 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=115.topic>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Could a nuclear interceptor be ready in 17 years?</span><hr size=1> Let's assume that the astronomical society confirms the threat of this latest asteroid to be real. That's a 2 kilometre hunk of rock gunning for us. How long would it take to get a big NERVA completed? At a congressional conference a couple of years back on this problem of asteroids hitting the Earth, one item on the discussion agenda was Super Orions. Could we throw one of those together in 17 years?<br>
Keep in mind that the proposed budget would be quite generous for any program instigated for saving the Earth. Red Tape would be, well, essentially non-existant.  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/uzaphod4468.showPublicProfile?language=EN>zaphod4468</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>ezOP</span><br>  Posts: 673<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(7/25/02 9:41 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=115.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.bbc.co.uk/cult/hitchhikers/gallery/images/100/zaphod2.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Could a nuclear interceptor be ready in 17 years?</span><hr size=1> I would think the 10-15 year time frame would work for a modest size Orion... assuming an endeavor equal to or exceeding that of the Apollo moon program... of course more would be at stake than a countries national pride as in the moon race. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/uarkuunaves.showPublicProfile?language=EN>ArkuunAves</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Cadet</span><br>  Posts: 27<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(7/25/02 3:27 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=115.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Could a nuclear interceptor be ready in 17 years?</span><hr size=1> I'm personally guessing it would take far less than 17 years, more along the lines of 5-10.<br>
<br>
The simple fact is...if it were confirmed, you'd have the US,Russia,EU,and China throwing together money and personnel to do something.<br>
<br>
Consider that the US, when turned towards a single cause, has done MASSIVE things in war time.  Then consider this &quot;war&quot; would literally be for the survival of our world. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/ubrp17.showPublicProfile?language=EN>brp17</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NEP Freighter Crewman</span><br>  Posts: 99<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(7/25/02 10:47 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=115.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Could a nuclear interceptor be ready in 17 years?</span><hr size=1> If we were going without a rushed cause, ei, if we decided that an Orion ship was a good idea and built one, we would be ready in I guess around 10 years. To build one for intercepting a meteor would be less than 5 years if needs be, possible as few as 2-3. It depends if it's orion or other nuclear, but any system really would do the trick for 17 years period. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/uzaphod4468.showPublicProfile?language=EN>zaphod4468</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>ezOP</span><br>  Posts: 681<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(7/26/02 9:45 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=115.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.bbc.co.uk/cult/hitchhikers/gallery/images/100/zaphod2.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Could a nuclear interceptor be ready in 17 years?</span><hr size=1> Are we talking about a 4000 ton Orion when we say 'Super Orion'?<br>
<br>
Would a Naval ship yard be the ideal place to build a Super Orion? <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/uprojectorion.showPublicProfile?language=EN>projectorion</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Nuclear Renaissance Man</span><br>  Posts: 1710<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(7/26/02 10:13 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=115.topic&index=5>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Orion or Nerva.</span><hr size=1> Unfortunately I dont have the minutes of the meeting. They are no longer available on the net. All I have seen is the itemised agenda as posted by john4303 at the old project orion club. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/ubrp17.showPublicProfile?language=EN>brp17</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NERVA Spaceplane Pilot</span><br>  Posts: 105<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(7/26/02 11:25 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=115.topic&index=6>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Orion or Nerva.</span><hr size=1> The levels of orion I think are something like this.<br>
<br>
200 tons or so is a satilite orion<br>
4000 tons or so is just orion<br>
I think super orion is around 1 million tons, but I could be wrong. The point is it's alot higher...<br>
<br>
As to nerva or orion, I'd say unless there's a good reason NERVA or a similar system. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/uzaphod4468.showPublicProfile?language=EN>zaphod4468</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>ezOP</span><br>  Posts: 685<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(7/27/02 9:51 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=115.topic&index=7>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.bbc.co.uk/cult/hitchhikers/gallery/images/100/zaphod2.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Orion or Nerva.</span><hr size=1> What about a big dumb conventional booster to place the parts of<br>
a 4000 ton class orion in orbit, bolt the thing together,<br>
bring up the pulse units and final crew last...? <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=x>X</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NERVA Spaceplane Pilot</span><br>  Posts: 107<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(7/27/02 5:17 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=115.topic&index=8>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/Bart-term.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Could a nuclear interceptor be ready in 17 years?</span><hr size=1> Who needs an Orion when you can blow that sucker into dust with a ten megaton nuke?  All you need a good-sized launch vehicle like the Delta-IV to launch a good size booster and a shuttle mission to place the nuke on the booster and send it off for an asteroid rendezvous.  Most of the pieces will either miss Earth due to scattering, be too small to survive the trip through the atmosphere, or can be destroyed by tactical nukes later on. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/ujohnfraz.showPublicProfile?language=EN>John Fraz</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_yingyang.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NERVA Spaceplane Pilot</span><br>  Posts: 155<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(8/1/02 9:41 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=115.topic&index=9>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://lneilsmith.com/tools/littlelogo.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/Bart-term.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: interceptor</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> &gt; Who needs an Orion when you can blow that sucker into dust with<br>
a ten megaton nuke?... Most of the pieces will either miss Earth due to<br>
scattering, be too small to survive the trip through the atmosphere, or<br>
